.SH "NAME"
mac\-pix \- convert Apple MacPaint bitmap into pix(5) or bw(5) raster image
.SH "SYNOPSIS"
.sp
\fBmac\-pix\fP [\-clb] [\-s \fIsquareMacSize\fP] [\-w \fIMac_width\fP] [\-n \fIMac_height\fP] [\-x \fIMac_xoff\fP] [\-y \fIMac_yoff\fP] [\-X \fIoutput_xoff\fP] [\-Y \fIoutput_yoff\fP] [\-S \fIsquareOutputSize\fP] [\-W \fIoutput_width\fP] [\-N \fIoutput_height\fP] [\-C \fIr/g/b\fP] [\fIfile.mac\fP]
.SH "DESCRIPTION"
.sp
\fBmac\-pix\fP reads an Apple MacIntosh MacPaint bitmap file and
generates a \fBpix\fP(5) or
\fBbw\fP(5) raster image file. While the MacPaint file
is 720x576 pixels, it is possible to specify an alternate size input
file with the \fB\-s\fP , \fB\-w\fP , and \fB\-n\fP flags; the
usefulness of this is unknown. By default, the output
\fBpix\fP(5) file is 1024x1024 pixels, with the input
image located in the lower left corner of the output (nearest the
origin).  The default color for an "on" pixel is white (R=G=B=255);
alternatively, the \fB\-C r/g/b\fP flag can be used to specify
intensities for each of the colors, in the range of [0..255]. The
\fB\-b\fP flag will output a \fBbw\fP(5) black and
white file instead. If the \fB\-c\fP flag is specified, the input
image is centered in the middle of the output image.
.sp
If the output width is set to 0 by the user, the input width is used
for the output width; similarly, if the output height is set to 0 by
the user, the input height is used for the output height.  Those
values of 0 can be set simultaneously by use of the \fB\-l\fP flag, so
that both width and height of the input are used. Alternatively, the
\fB\-S\fP flag can be used to specify the square output size, or
\fB\-W\fP and \fB\-N\fP flags can be used to specify the output width
and height.
.sp
If no input file is specified, standard input is read instead.
.sp
The \fB\-x\fP and \fB\-y\fP flags can be used to specify the input x
and y offset. The \fB\-X\fP and \fB\-Y\fP flags can be used to specify
the output x and y offset.
.SH "EXAMPLE"
.sp
Especially pleasing displays of MacPaint documents can be made by
using \fBpixmerge\fP(1) to combine them with the
output of \fBpixbackgnd\fP(1):
.sp
.if n .RS 4
.nf
pixbackgnd \-H 160 200 > bg.pix

mac\-pix \-c file.mac | pixmerge \- bg.pix | pix\-fb
.fi
